Accelerating battery research with an AI interface between FINALES and Kadi4Mat
Abstract
The time-consuming formation process critically impacts the longevity of sodium‑ion coin cells and End Of Life (EOL) performance. This study aims to optimize formation protocols for duration efficiency, targeting high-performance outcomes while minimizing the number of experiments to reduce resource consumption and accelerate discovery. Specifically, we consider two potentially competing objectives: minimizing formation time and maximizing EOL performance. Beyond this application focus, we also present a methodological contribution: a framework designed to enable interoperability between the Fast-INtention Agnostic LEarning Server (FINALES) and Kadi Research Data Management (RDM) ecosystems, which we employ to tackle our optimization problem. In this setup, the FINALES framework orchestrates experiment planning and execution on the Post-Lithium Storage Cluster of Excellence (POLiS) Materials Acceleration Platform (MAP), while an active-learning agent implemented within Kadi4Mat guides experiment selection, using multi-objective batched Bayesian optimization to efficiently explore the parameter space. This interoperability enhancement enables coordinated, distributed collaboration across automated systems and human-operated workflows, bridging multiple research centers. Using this approach, we iteratively explore the trade-off between formation time and EOL performance and identify candidate solutions approximating the Pareto front. The resulting workflow demonstrates the capability of interoperable infrastructures to facilitate data-driven optimization in battery research, and establishes a transferable framework applicable to diverse materials science and engineering optimization tasks.
Keywords Active Learning Battery Bayesian Optimization End Of Life FINALES Formation Kadi4Mat KadiAI Material Acceleration Platform Sodium-Ion
1 Introduction
Accelerating battery development has become increasingly important as demand for cost-efficient, sustainable energy storage technologies grows. The battery production chain involves several key steps: material preparation, electrode production, cell manufacturing, and cell conditioning [kwade2018current]. High costs and extended cell conditioning times significantly slow innovation and consume substantial resources. Notably, the longest steps that occur during the conditioning phase are formation and aging process, which can last up to 24 hours [heimes2018lithium] and three weeks [heimes2020effects, wood2019formation] respectively. Formation is considered one of the key steps determining battery quality, whereas during aging, quality and safety parameters are monitored. The associated costs of the formation and aging processes account for approximately [nelson2019modeling, borner2024prozessbasiertes, hakimian2015economic] to [kwade2018current, liu2021current] of the total cell production expenses. Part of these costs is the necessary equipment, which accounts for a significant amount of floor space, up to of the entire production facility [wood2019formation]. Formation procedures are highly material-dependent and rarely directly transferable. Furthermore, scaling from small lab cells (e.g., coin cells) to large industrial formats is challenging due to the emergence of new behaviors [scurtu2025small]. For these reasons, the formation process, as a critical bottleneck in battery manufacturing, is a closely guarded secret and has received particular attention in optimization research. Promising current approaches for optimization and accelerated discovery aim to combine automated workflows and experiments of Materials Acceleration Platforms (MAPs) [vogler2023brokering, vogler2024autonomous, dave2020autonomous, wagner2021evolution, walter2010combinatorial, burger2020mobile] guided by machine learning models [rahmanian2022enabling, sanin2025integrating, geslin2025dynamic]. MAPs with focus on optimizing material properties or reaction pathways only rarely account for processes at the device level, such as formation. The Fast-INtention Agnostic LEarning Server (FINALES) framework combines both and was demonstrated to identify an optimized electrolyte formulation regarding conductivity and End Of Life (EOL) [vogler2024autonomous, vogler2023brokering].
The EOL is a cell quality indicator for the maximum application duration commonly described by the number of cycles, after which the capacity of the cell falls below – of its initial capacity [wang2022prospects, chen2019recycling, ramoni2013end, saxena2015quantifying]. While high-throughput experimentation enabled by automation implicitly assumes that all relevant process steps can be automated. In practice, however, certain process steps remain difficult or undesirable to automate [Hung2024Autonomous, Gary2024SelfDriving], for example, due to safety constraints [scheurer2025role]. Recent publications are targeting the formation and its acceleration using machine learning models and data-driven approaches, mostly for known lithium-ion-based systems [CUI20243072, STOCK2024234858], leaving upcoming chemistries such as sodium-ion batteries unexplored.
Given the constraints on battery development, data-driven materials process design, integrated with human expertise, offers a promising approach for efficient parameter optimization. Machine learning methods are increasingly used to support such optimization tasks, particularly in settings where data acquisition is cost-intensive. Active Learning is a subset of machine learning that focuses on sequentially selecting the most informative experiment configuration, aiming to improve sample efficiency while reducing overall experimental cost. As an active-learning query strategy, Bayesian optimization provides a model-driven, uncertainty-aware approach for identifying promising regions of a design space using relatively few evaluations compared with traditional methods such as grid or random search. This makes it a powerful tool for navigating complex, high-dimensional material landscapes. Previous work [liang2021benchmarking, rohr2020benchmarking, stein2022materials, kulagin2023LatticeMetamaterialsMesoscale, zhao2023CharacterizationPorousMembranes] demonstrated that such an approach significantly outperforms classic search methods across diverse materials systems, achieving superior results with fewer experiments. Specifically to battery research, [zhao2022machine] developed a machine learning framework to optimize the synthesis of Lithium Aluminum Titanium Phosphate, and [JeelaTosato2025BayesianSOFC] efficiently identified optimal model parameters for simulating the aging of nickel-gadolinium-doped ceria anodes. Interactive human-in-the-loop workflows extend this paradigm by allowing domain experts to interpret and execute suggested parameter configurations as physical experiments, feed the resulting measurements back into the active-learning cycle, and, when necessary, impose domain knowledge or feasibility and steer the learning process. In this work, we build on these concepts to develop a model that iteratively learns from cycling experiments on sodium-ion coin cells to balance formation efficiency and long-term degradation. Specifically, we formulate an optimization problem with two potentially competing objectives: minimizing formation time and maximizing EOL performance.
In parallel with the optimization objective, this work addresses a methodological challenge in distributed experimental environments related to Research Data Management (RDM). Modern battery research increasingly relies on heterogeneous RDM systems to store, process, and exchange experimental data. However, limited interoperability between such systems often hinders efficient data reuse, coordination, and automation across platforms. To address this limitation, we present a framework that enables interoperability between two complementary RDM ecosystems: Kadi and the FINALES-based Post-Lithium Storage Cluster of Excellence (POLiS) MAP. The Kadi ecosystem consists of multiple instances, among which Kadi4Mat serves as the virtual research environment that manages data, metadata, and workflow automation. It combines repository functionality for data management with electronic lab notebook capabilities and a plugin system, all of which enable the documentation and automation of research processes. The FINALES framework orchestrates experiment planning and execution on the POLiS MAP via so-called tenants, which combine automated capabilities with tasks performed by human researchers, and implement the MAP concept for process optimization at the device level. To bridge these systems, we establish interoperable links via dedicated plugins and tenants (see Fig.˜1). The resulting interactive optimization framework enables machine-learning-guided studies that deploy automated laboratory experimentation coupled with human-in-the-loop process steps.
2 Results and Discussion
The main results of this work consist of two complementary components: methodological developments and application-oriented findings. The first component, presented in Section˜2.1, introduces our interactive optimization framework. We consider this framework a result in itself, as it demonstrates, through the Kadi-FINALES coupling, how interoperability among RDM systems can enhance data exchange, promote reuse and reproducibility, improve operational efficiency, and ultimately accelerate research processes. The second component, presented in Section˜2.2, reports the outcomes of the optimization study conducted with this framework, and the identified trade-off between formation time and end-of-life performance.
2.1 Methodological results: the human-in-the-loop optimization framework
In this section, we present the workflow implemented for the active-learning agent and laboratory operations, and describe the data flow between these processes, from the operating user to the MAP and back. The developed framework combines complementary functionalities of Kadi4Mat and FINALES, enabling synchronized operations that support automated, human-in-the-loop optimization.
Figure˜1 shows the workflow sequence at a conceptual level. The data flow begins within the Kadi ecosystem, where parameter optimization and FAIR data management are performed. In Kadi4Mat, the user defines the optimization problem via a user-friendly template, which generates a central (“umbrella”) record linking all study components. The KadiAIgent plugin responds to umbrella record activation and interfaces with Computational Intelligence and Data Science framework (CIDS), enabling our active-learning Bayesian optimization framework. The optimizer follows a goal-aware, information-driven learning strategy, iteratively selecting experiments that are the most informative with respect to the target objectives defined for the study. Using a multiphase generation strategy, the KadiAIgent identifies the most informative parameter configurations within the defined search space for the next batch of experiments. The resulting information is then submitted to the FINALES server via the FINALES plugin, which translates it from the Kadi representation into a FINALES-compatible request, thereby configuring the corresponding experiments. The Kadi ecosystem now waits for FINALES to deliver the experimental results so Kadi can score and complete the current batch of trials. Further details on the active-learning method and the Kadi components of the framework are provided in Section˜4.1.
In the second part of the loop, FINALES receives the workflow request from the FINALES plugin, and passes it to the workflow management tenant OVERLooking ORchestrating Tenant (OVERLORT). The OVERLORT coordinates the execution of the workflow by orchestrating the individual services within the automated laboratory. This includes fully automated tasks, such as cell assembly, as well as manually performed tasks, such as formulating and transporting electrolyte or cells to the next device. The full workflow is described in Section˜4.3. A higher degree of automation is possible, but the executing scientists provide quality control and monitoring. Once all results are available, the OVERLORT posts a request to upload data, which is handled by the Kadi tenant. The results are automatically uploaded to Kadi4Mat in a predefined data structure and incorporated into the dataset to improve subsequent steps in the search. Further details on the FINALES components of the framework are provided in Section˜4.2.
Since data in both FINALES and Kadi4Mat are represented as JSON structures, they are inherently human- and machine-readable. Augmented by the Kadi4Mat web interface, the data representation becomes more intuitive for human users, thereby enhancing the user-friendliness of the data generated in the POLiS MAP. Moreover, the connection to Kadi4Mat not only provides tools for data visualization but also enables researchers to add observations that automated procedures may miss. In this demonstration, Kadi4Mat provided an interface for human researchers to add notes, additional warnings or report errors in the dataset, which allowed for proper handling of the affected data points. This results in thorough digital documentation and increased traceability for decisions, such as outlier detection. Moreover, accessibility for human researchers opens the possibility of integrating non-automated laboratories into MAPs running on FINALES. This enables a more inclusive research strategy and exploits the high flexibility of non-automated processes (cf. [Gary2024SelfDriving]), which can typically be performed with only minimal standardization. Finally, standardized automated procedures and their respective code bases can be shared and reused, using the invested development resources efficiently and improving the reproducibility of experiments.
Since Kadi4Mat serves a central role in communication and information exchange between the KadiAIgent and the POLiS MAP, all data associated with requests and corresponding results are recorded in Kadi4Mat. There, data are shared with all project partners, enabling continuous access and evaluation for all parties throughout the study. Furthermore, the publication of the data for a larger community is significantly facilitated compared to first storing all data locally and subsequently uploading them manually at the end of the study. Kadi4Mat allows exporting the data and associated metadata of a record and directly publishing it in external repositories such as Zenodo.
2.2 Application results: multi-objective optimization of Sodium ion coin-cell formation time and cycle life
The multi-objective optimization study was designed to identify formation protocols that simultaneously maximize cell lifetime while minimizing formation time. The search space is defined by three parameters: the charge and discharge rates during formation, and the number of formation cycle repetitions. The considered ranges for each parameter are shown in Table˜1. Two competing objectives were considered: maximizing the EOL cycle number and minimizing the total formation time. To improve efficiency, the optimization was performed in a batch setting. Up to three batches were evaluated in parallel at each iteration of the optimization loop. Furthermore, to reduce errors and minimize the impact of potential outliers, each batch comprised four cells with identical configuration settings. The reported metrics correspond to the mean values obtained across these four cells. Details on the experimental setups can be found in Section˜4.3.
Our study includes a total of 18 batches, indexed from 0 to 17 (see Table˜2). A stopping criterion based on the experimental duration and associated resource demands was applied to conclude the optimization study. Consequently, the cycling cells of batch 17 which exhibited high EOL were discontinued accordingly. The data and metadata associated with each cycling cell in these batches are stored in individual, linked records in Kadi4Mat (see Fig.˜8). An overview of the optimization results for each batch is presented in Table˜2, including the selected parameter configuration and the corresponding mean metric values.
Figure˜2 provides an overview of the objective space with the obtained EOL and formation time values for the sampled formation protocols. For lithium-ion batteries, neither long nor short formation times yield good long-term performance [mao2018balancing], and a similar trend is expected for sodium-ion batteries. Based on the in-sample average, the data suggest an optimized formation time of approximately . This matches the Pareto solution with the best EOL performance (batch 15), which reports a formation time of with low standard error.
Within the scope of the experimental study, the latest set of parameters tested included four formation cycles with a charge rate of and a discharge rate of . From Table˜2 it can be seen that batch 17 shows an average EOL of , which is consistent with predictions, but significantly higher than the average EOL of all the other batches. Consequently, the evaluation of the results is strongly influenced by whether this batch is included in the evaluation or not. The property charts presented in Fig.˜3 show the contour plots prior to the inclusion of batch 17. The contour plots for batch 17 are available in the Supporting Information (SI). Based on the contour plots in Fig.˜13, the parameter set of batch 17 should be expected to result in a long EOL. However, based on the data available in this study, it cannot be ruled out that batch 17 is an outlier, and further investigation is necessary to verify this performance.
From the evaluation of batches 0-16, the best average cycle life ( cycles, ) was observed after the formation with a charge rate of , a discharge rate of for cycles (see Table˜2). The same results are visualized in Fig.˜3, where an optimal rate region around is observed for both charge (Figs.˜3(a) and 3(b)) and discharge (Figs.˜3(a) and 3(c)). Details about maximum charge and discharge capacity over cycles of the four cells constituting the considered Pareto optimal solution, are shown in Fig.˜4. It should be noted that the inclusion of batch 17 in the analysis shifts the optimum to approximately , as illustrated in the SI, Fig.˜13. Batch 0 already suggests good performance at higher rates, whereas batch 7 indicates a negative influence of very high rates for charge and discharge. Batch 16 using rates of and for 4 repetitions results in a good trade-off between formation time () and cycle life (), with no scattering among the four cells tested.
The model expects a capacity evolution over time during the formation cycles as inputs and may adjust the charge and discharge rates used during formation and the number of formation cycles. The charge and discharge rates in this study are referenced to the theoretical capacity of the coin cells, , for all batches to determine the charging and discharging currents. The model further predicts the number of cycles the cell can endure before reaching of the initial capacity in the first discharge cycle after formation.
3 Conclusion
The presented active-learning optimization framework integrates the functionalities of Kadi4Mat and FINALES. Both systems were jointly extended to enable efficient data exchange and closed-loop interaction between experimental control, data management, and decision-making. The framework’s utility and efficiency are showcased through this study, where we employed it to optimize formation time and end-of-life performance of sodium-ion coin cells. Shorter formation protocols, although reducing experimental time, may alter interphase formation and consequently affect long-term performance. Therefore, the objectives of this study do not scale proportionally and require joint optimization to identify a solution that balances formation efficiency and cell longevity. Our multi-objective optimization framework successfully handled this tension by identifying a Pareto front. This identifies the set of solutions in which formation time cannot be reduced further without decreasing EOL cycle life, and EOL cycle life cannot be increased further without increasing formation time. Our work showcases a unified learning framework in which human expertise and artificial intelligence operate in sync. The balance between automated learning and human guidance can be tailored by systematically allocating control over distinct stages of the learning process to different agents. The system’s modular architecture and open-source foundation make it highly extensible and adaptable to various scientific domains, beyond materials science. Looking forward, this framework naturally supports increasing levels of automation. For instance, a voice-responsive chatbot built on [zhao2025LISALithiumIonSolidState] could assist researchers by logging errors or warnings into the Kadi record, reducing manual documentation while preserving expert oversight.
4 Methods
4.1 The KadiAIgent active-learning framework in the Kadi ecosystem
The proposed active-learning framework operates within the Kadi ecosystem, which is built around Kadi instances that host the core repository and web frontend [brandt2021kadi4mat]. Through its modular components and plugin architecture, the Kadi ecosystem enables users to create data records and to initiate events and automated workflows [griem2022kadistudio]. The constituent modules of the Kadi ecosystem communicate through well-defined interfaces, enabling seamless coordination of events and information flow. This design explicitly supports scientists and laboratory technicians as the primary operators. For instance, advanced visualization and dashboard generation features make it possible to follow the optimization process in real time. A further support for researchers’ daily tasks within the Kadi ecosystem is KadiStudio [griem2022kadistudio], a standalone desktop application that enables visual design and execution of scientific workflows through an interactive, graphical editor.
To start the optimization process, the operating user accesses the Kadi instance through the web interface, where data and associated metadata are organized as records (basic structured data entry of Kadi4Mat). By default, records require only a minimal set of generic metadata (e.g., title and identifier), which is automatically enriched with system-generated information such as timestamps of the most recent changes. Through templates, the metadata structure of records, including keys (labels, names), identifiers, validation, and pre-filled values, can be predefined for different applications and research domains. The active-learning tool provides an umbrella template for arbitrary optimization and design studies. From that template, users can create umbrella records whose metadata fully define their own design study, including design parameters, optimization objectives (or metrics), constraints on the output, and optimization settings. The latter supports a multiphase generation strategy in which each phase is user-configurable, including the number of initial random (or Sobol) trials and the selection of the kernel and acquisition function for the surrogate model. A single optimized parameter rarely captures the full structural or functional diversity of a material. Therefore, multi-objective optimization is often necessary to balance competing or interdependent properties and identify robust design solutions. In the present study, we address these limitations by extending our active-learning framework to experimental data, enabling both multi-objective and constrained optimization. Specifically, we developed a data-driven active-learning model that guides parameter tuning to minimize formation duration while maximizing the EOL of coin cells.
Kadi instances provide a plugin system that uses hooks to listen for events and trigger actions. The framework presented here uses two plugins: the KadiAIgent active-learning plugin for sequential decision-making within the optimization loop, and the FINALES plugin for communication with FINALES. Both plugins automatically manage access and permissions for the involved records, ensuring that only authorized users can trigger events.
KadiAIgent is an advanced active-learning agent that integrates the Ax adaptive experimentation platform [olson2025ax] with CIDS [koeppe2023cids] as part of KadiAI, the Machine Learning and Artificial Intelligence interface of Kadi4Mat. CIDS provides modular, flexible AI infrastructure specifically designed to handle diverse scientific applications in engineering, materials science, and the natural sciences. The KadiAIgent active-learning plugin integrates Bayesian optimization into the Kadi ecosystem to guide the adaptive exploration of design parameter spaces, while automating the experimental optimization process. Based on an event marking the start of an optimization loop iteration, the active-learning plugin creates trial records for the optimization problem defined in the umbrella record. Specifically, the triggering event is either adding the !kadiaigent-al-umbrella-active tag to an umbrella record, indicating that the study configuration is complete, or adding the !kadiaigent-al-trial-completed tag to a trial record associated with an active umbrella record, indicating successful trial completion. Both these events trigger a new iteration, creating a new trial record that encodes the metadata for a specific configuration of each design parameter. The new trial is then automatically linked to the umbrella record via a link labeled !kadiaigent-al-trial-for. The decision on which configuration to try next is made using a multi-objective Bayesian optimization method. Bayesian optimization builds a probabilistic surrogate model of the experiment’s objective function, allowing it to predict promising parameter settings together with their uncertainties. Initial data points are required for the model to start constructing a probabilistic map of the search space. In the absence of such data, the model lacks knowledge of the objective functions, leading to uniformly high uncertainty across the entire domain. For the present study, instead of using Sobol-sampled initial points, we leveraged 11 previously available data points from a previous study. The selected samples align with current practice for human-based investigations and thus represent the human expertise component of this human-lab-AI integrative concept. Further details are provided in Section˜4.6. To offload potentially expensive computations from the repository server to a dedicated computing node, Bayesian inference is implemented as a separate service [koeppe2023cids, koeppe2021deep]. The active-learning plugin communicates with this Bayesian inference server through REST requests. Finally, the KadiAIgent active-learning plugin adds two tags to the trial record: !kadiaigent-al-trial-running to track the trial state, and !to-finales to trigger a communication request to FINALES through the FINALES plugin.
The FINALES plugin in Kadi provides the interface that allows the KadiAIgent active-learning plugin to communicate directly with FINALES, extending the system’s interoperability with external platforms. To define the experimental workflow, we provide a blueprint as a FINALES base workflow record in Kadi, and link it to the umbrella record via the !finales-baseworkflow-for link. The base workflow record contains metadata extracted from a JSON file, a widely used format in web-based applications, making the FINALES plugin easily adaptable to other web-based services. As an event, the FINALES plugin detects the tag !to-finales added to a trial record. This event triggers the extraction of the trial configuration as key-value pairs from the trial record. By tracing the knowledge graph, i.e., following the links from the trial to the umbrella and on to the base workflow record, the FINALES plugin extracts the blueprint for the experimental workflow to be executed through FINALES. After filling in the key-value pairs, a FINALES workflow record is created to store the experimental workflow instructions for FINALES as metadata. Finally, the workflow is submitted to the FINALES server via the HTTP-based REST API, and the workflow record receives the state tag !finales-request-running.
4.2 Experimental workflow
Upon successful submission via the HTTP-based REST API, the workflow is received and processed by the FINALES system, which orchestrates the experiment’s execution. To perform closed-loop optimization, we adapted the previously reported FINALES system [vogler2023brokering, vogler2024autonomous] and implemented a tenant that automatically uploads the generated data to the Kadi4Mat platform upon completion. Within FINALES, individual tenants (i.e., software or hardware clients providing specific capabilities to the system) were registered with the following functionality: Autonomous Battery Assembly System (AutoBASS) tenant (assembling coin cells), Cycler tenant (battery cycling), Transportation tenant (transportation of physical samples), OVERLORT (workflow management), KadiAIgent (active-learning optimizer), and Kadi Tenant (upload results to Kadi4Mat in a structured way).
Each iteration in the laboratory starts with a workflow execution request, posted to FINALES via the FINALES plugin in Kadi, which directs the assembly and cycling of coin cells according to a specified C-rate for formation charge and discharge, as well as a defined number of formation cycle repetitions. Figure˜5 shows the sequence of events performed at the CELEST Green Energy Lab Ulm.
After pulling the workflow request from FINALES, the OVERLORT posts the first sub-request and waits for the corresponding result before posting the next one. To do so, the OVERLORT keeps track of active workflows and their respective most recent requests in an internal queue, which is regularly updated as shown in Fig.˜6. As a first step in the workflow, the OVERLORT requests the reservation of cycling channels and the required number of channels is flagged as reserved at the battery cycler. Subsequently, the electrolyte formulation is requested by the OVERLORT. The electrolyte was manually formulated by a human researcher, who also entered the corresponding batch data into a JSON structure posted to FINALES. Likewise, the electrolyte was manually transferred to the AutoBASS and loaded into a vial. The automatic cell assembly used the provided electrolyte and cell components, including the disk-shaped electrodes and separator. In the next step, the cells were transported to their reserved channels at the battery cycler outside the glovebox. After completing the manual transfer, a human researcher confirmed the transport using the Transportation tenant. This confirmation closed the transport request, and the OVERLORT submitted a request to cycle the cells, which prompted the cycler tenant to create the test protocol and start the tests at the respective channels. Upon finishing the test, the automatic export of the data, after which the OVERLORT posts the final result related to the workflow request, requests the upload of the data to Kadi4Mat, and removes the workflow from its internal queue. On Kadi4Mat, the optimizer accesses the data, processes it, and based on the newly acquired knowledge, sends the next workflow request.
To avoid an excessive number of experiments and to enable our information-driven strategy to make the most of each new data point, only three batches of cells were allowed to run in parallel. Each batch comprised four cells assembled with the same materials and parameters.
4.3 Coin cell assembly and testing
Coin cells (CR2032) were automatically assembled by the in-house developed robotic AutoBASS-system [zhang2022robotic, zhang2024apples] in a nitrogen-filled glovebox. The coin cell parts were washed with isopropyl alcohol in an ultrasonic bath and dried together with the Glass fiber separator (Whatman GF/C™) at . The components were subsequently stored in the glovebox until cell assembly. Carbon-coated sodium vanadium phosphate \chNa3V2(PO4)3/C (NVP/C) was used as the cathode material, and the commercial hard carbon material KURANODE™ Type II from KURARAY CO., LTD was used as active material in the anode. Both electrode materials were supplied, and the NVP/C was also synthesized by the Institute for Applied Materials (IAM) at the Karlsruhe Institute of Technology (KIT). Details about the electrode preparation and characterization can be found in [stuble2024powder]. The cathodes, anodes, and separators were cut into discs of diameters , , and , respectively. of \chNaPF6 in ethylene carbonate (EC): propylene carbonate (PC) (1:1 by weight) was used as the electrolyte. The electrolyte was manually formulated in batches of approximately with only a few batches being larger or smaller. During the cell assembly process, the AutoBASS [zhang2022robotic, zhang2024apples] dosed the electrolyte into the coin cells using its pipetting module.
The nominal capacity for all cells was calculated to be based on the areal cathode capacity of . The cells were cycled at a controlled temperature of on an Arbin battery cycler (model LBT21084-5). The test protocols include formation cycle(s) at various C-rates and repetitions, as well as cycling using constant current constant voltage (CCCV) charging at C/5 up to (C/20 cut-off) and C/5 discharging until the cell voltage falls below . The cycling was repeated until a threshold of of the remaining discharge capacity was reached, using the first cycle as the reference.
4.4 Closing the loop with the human researcher
In Kadi, the FINALES plugin finds the result records uploaded by the FINALES Kadi tenant. Two approaches are possible: On the one hand, a metadatum in the workflow record stores the request UUID returned by the FINALES instance, which can be used to search for uploaded result records that also contain this UUID, even across different Kadi instances. On the other hand, the FINALES plugin can detect record links added to the workflow record that includes the request, thereby identifying results belonging to that workflow record. In the present study, we used the first option because development was performed on a dedicated test Kadi instance, whereas FINALES communicated results from a production Kadi instance.
Based on the result records, the FINALES plugin extracts and evaluates cycling data and parameters. A Python script analyzes the cycling curves for each assembled cell per batch by extracting characteristic points and computing the mean and SEM for both objectives. In addition, because design parameters may deviate from the original workflow request due to intrinsic device uncertainty, errors, or human overrides based on intuition and experience, the data points are updated with the actual measured design parameters. Finally, the FINALES plugin saves the updated design parameters and objective metrics in the workflow and trial records. It changes their state tags to !finales-request-completed and !kadiaigent-al-trial-completed, respectively.
The optimization loop can be closed either manually or by the KadiAIgent active-learning plugin, which detects new completed trials. Based on that event trigger, the active-learning plugin accumulates data from all completed trials linked to the umbrella. The measured parameter configurations and corresponding objective metrics and variances are used to fit a Gaussian process model for Bayesian inference (Section˜4.6). The inferred most-informative parameter values serve as trial configurations for the subsequent loop iterations of the design study.
To visualize the progress of the optimization study, umbrella records can be enhanced with dashboards (Fig.˜7). The dashboards provide interactive plots that visualize trade-offs and the optimization process’s progress, along with contour plots of the objectives. Each Bayesian inference run updates the interactive plots. Internally, the dashboards are implemented in Python through the dash and plotly libraries, which export interactive plots as JSON objects. These JSON objects can be embedded directly in the Kadi instance’s web interface under the corresponding record.
4.5 Data structure and knowledge graph
In FINALES, all services, whether physical setups in a laboratory or computations on a server or a computing cluster, are registered as so-called tenants. Upon registration, each tenant obtains a unique identifier (UUID), referred to as the tenant-UUID, from FINALES, which uniquely identifies the tenant. Prior to registering a tenant, the tenant developer and the FINALES administrator define the input and output data structures for the tenant. Requests and results posted to FINALES are validated against these data structures and rejected if they are not compliant. Each tenant provides one or more capabilities to the MAP by querying FINALES and posting requests or results depending on its task. A capability in this context is defined as a combination of a certain quantity and a method that yields a value for this quantity. In the scope of FINALES, a quantity is not limited to a measurable, physical quantity but can also be defined as a label for the output of a service (e.g., transportation).
All requests and results that are posted to FINALES are stored in an SQL database. FINALES assigns a unique identifier (UUID) to each request and result to enable traceability and link results to their corresponding requests. It also adds a timestamp to the request to document the time when it was received by FINALES. Finally, FINALES assigns the status pending to the request. This is crucial for tenants to pick up tasks, as they usually query FINALES regularly for pending requests that align with their capabilities. Apart from this metadata that is automatically added by FINALES, a request object contains the parameters that specify the requested result. This means it includes all relevant information about the parameters or inputs needed to execute the method that generates the requested data, and, if applicable, also a specification of the sample under investigation.
A tenant that picked up the request performs its tasks using these inputs and generates a result, or it processes the results available through FINALES and posts a new request. The results posted to FINALES also obey to a structure similar to the requests. The body of the result contains the data obtained by the tenant in the output format that was defined by the FINALES administrator and the tenant developer. Analogous to the requests, metadata such as a UUID, a timestamp, and a status are automatically assigned by FINALES once the result gets posted. An important difference between requests and results is that the latter include the UUID of the request they reply to, establishing a link. Moreover, the result not only reports the parameters actually used when performing its tasks but also the parameters and inputs provided in the request. This allows for the comparison of targeted and actual parameter values, which may, for example, be used to identify severe discrepancies.
In this study, seven tenants with varying capabilities interact with FINALES. These tenants are:
-
•
KadiAIgent – The tenant related to the agent processing all the data available via FINALES to generate new requests.
-
•
OVERLORT – The workflow manager used in the self-driving laboratory to ensure the correct sequence of events.
-
•
Cycler – The tenant connected to the automated battery cycler.
-
•
Electrolyte – The tenant responsible for the human researcher who prepared the electrolyte solutions.
-
•
Transportation – The tenant coordinating the transport of physical components in the laboratory.
-
•
AutoBASS – The tenant connected to the Automated Battery Assembly System (AutoBASS).
-
•
Kadi4Mat – The tenant used for the automated upload of the data to the Kadi4Mat data management platform.
Each tenant has its own data structures for inputs and outputs, since the applicable structures depend on each tenant’s capabilities. FINALES provides an endpoint for querying data structures registered for a specific capability. Based on the definitions of data structures in JSON schemas, both human users and programs interfacing with FINALES can read and process them.
Within the SQL database of FINALES, links between requests, results, tenants, and other objects are traceable using the UUIDs assigned to each element in the database. Although this enables traceability, the lack of visualization makes it challenging for a human researcher to quickly grasp the relations and get an overview. Also, it was decided not to save data files in a binary format in the SQL database, even though this is technically possible.
Kadi4Mat enables human researchers to get an overview more quickly. Therefore, the Kadi4Mat tenant not only uploads data for storage but also defines a structured hierarchy of collections, records, and links. In this study, the structure created in Kadi4Mat is designed around a campaign and a study. The campaign used in this study is called Auto-POLiS. A campaign can relate to a high-level structure, such as a research project or a research group. Before starting a new campaign, the administrator can create a collection and a record for it. A campaign can include several studies that are closely linked to it, e.g., through funding. A study is also represented by a collection and a record in Kadi4Mat. The study presented here is labeled Human-Lab-AI, and the corresponding record and collection in Kadi4Mat are shown at the center of Fig.˜9. A reduced view of the knowledge graph, focusing on the records related to the KadiAIgent is shown in Fig.˜8. The umbrella record at the center holds the full optimization configuration and connects to the FINALES interface. This umbrella record is linked to each and every individual trial records, which contain all data and metadata for specific branch cells. In turn, each trial record is linked to a FINALES request record, used to communicate with the FINALES instance and trigger a FINALES workflow. The user can control the request record to start, stop, and evaluate the workflow using tags. Collections enable the grouping of records, helping human researchers more easily find data related to a study. With the additional use of a record, it is possible to create relations in the form of links between the records related to a study.
The next layer around the study record comprises workflow records. These represent the results posted by the OVERLORT for requests posted by the KadiAIgent. All results related to a workflow are represented as a record in Kadi4Mat and linked to their corresponding workflow record. This includes results for the reservation of cycling channels via the service method, results posted after the formulation of an electrolyte solution, and results related to executed transports, assembly, and cycling. Since coin cell assembly is requested in batches of four cells, each workflow includes one record with autobass_assembly in its label, but four records for the cycling of one cell each.
After each workflow request is posted to FINALES, the data is uploaded to Kadi4Mat, generating a linked set of records. The graphical representation of the structures shown in Fig.˜9 enables human researchers to gain an overview of the study and the relationships among the results. Since the Kadi4Mat tenant adds a group of users as administrators to each record, data can be easily shared or unshared with users by adding or removing them from the group. If different studies use distinct user groups, permissions can be managed easily, and fine-grained access control is possible.
Since the data are provided in structured, machine-readable formats in FINALES and Kadi4Mat, mappings to ontologies such as BattINFO [Clark2022Toward, Clark2023BattINFO] can be created. As part of the future development of FINALES and its data structures, mappings to ontologies could either directly be implemented as part of the FINALES schemas, or they could be implemented in tenants that can apply predefined mappings of the keys in the FINALES schemas to ontology terms. The latter option allows multiple tenants to deploy mappings to different ontologies. Such functionality could also be included in tenants, such as the Kadi4Mat tenant, if a platform requires a specific ontology.
4.6 Multi-objective Bayesian optimization
A multi-objective optimization problem aims to simultaneously optimize multiple objective functions. Specifically, it can be defined as:
where denotes a candidate solution in the search space , and specifies the competing objectives functions . In this formulation, the problem involves decision variables that define an -dimensional decision space and an -dimensional objective space. In multi-objective optimization problems, the mutually competing objectives create unavoidable trade-offs. Consequently, unlike in the single-objective setting, optimization methods cannot find a unique optimal solution, since no single solution can simultaneously optimize all objectives. Given two solutions x and , we say that x dominates (denoted as ) if is not worse than for any individual objective, and it exists at least one objective for which it is better, i.e.:
The optimization goal is to identify non-dominated solutions, i.e., solutions for which no objective can be improved without degrading at least one other. The subset of the search space containing all such solutions is referred to as the Pareto set:
The Pareto front denotes the corresponding set of points in the objective space obtained by mapping the Pareto set through the objective functions.
Bayesian optimization [garnett2023bayesian] has emerged as a major approach for multi-objective optimization, targeting black-box, derivative-free, and potentially non-convex functions that are computationally or resource-intensive. To this end, the method creates and iteratively updates a probabilistic surrogate model of each objective. This approach is built upon Bayesian inference, which provides a statistical principle for updating a probabilistic model of an unknown function as new data are collected, allowing uncertainty to be quantified and progressively reduced. A typical choice to formalize learning is to place a Gaussian Process (GP) prior [williams2006gaussian] as a surrogate model,
where is the mean function and the covariance kernel, encoding respectively the model’s prediction and uncertainty in the objective function. The learning process occurs when the GP prior, conditioned on the observed data points, yields a GP posterior that provides a distributional prediction at any . This posterior information is then used to construct an acquisition function, whose maximum identifies the most informative data point to query next, while balancing exploration and exploitation. To avoid assumptions about correlations between objectives that may not hold (e.g., if one objective is noisy while another is smooth), we chose a single-task, independent-GP framework, with each GP modeling only one objective. These independent surrogate models are subsequently combined into the acquisition function, thereby integrating information from all objectives.
Specifically for our study, we chose a Matérn GP kernel:
where is the length-scale controlling decay, is a modified Bessel function of the second kind, and we set the smoothness parameter . Matérn provides a suitable balance between modeling realistic experimental noise and capturing non-smooth variations in the objective landscape. To jointly exploit predictive means and uncertainties from all surrogate models, we adopted a hypervolume-based acquisition strategy. The hypervolume (HV) of a finite estimated Pareto front , with respect to a referent point , is the -dimensional Lebesgue measure of the space dominated by and bounded from below by r:
where denotes the hyper-rectangle bounded by vertices r and . Hypervolume improvement is considered an excellent, state-of-the-art metric for multi-objective optimization, as it simultaneously evaluates convergence to the true Pareto front and solution diversity. that efficiently drives algorithms towards the optimum. In particular, among the family of hypervolume improvement methods, we selected the q-noisy Expected Hypervolume Improvement (qNEHVI) [daulton2020differentiable] acquisition function to account for noise in experimental measurements while guiding our active-learning optimization loop. qNEHVI is well-suited for batch optimization and noisy settings, offers more computational efficiency than qEHVI, and is mathematically equivalent in the noiseless limit.
